{"id":"1207.0861","submitter":"Jos\\'e Ram\\'on Darias Gonz\\'alez","authors":"G. Guti\\'errez, C. Colonnello, P. Boltenhagen, J. R. Darias, R.\n  Peralta-Fabi, F. Brau, E. Cl\\'ement","title":"Silo collapse under granular discharge","comments":"Original work, 13 pages and 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate, at a laboratory scale, the collapse of cylindrical shells of\nradius $R$ and thickness $t$ induced by a granular discharge. We measure the\ncritical filling height for which the structure fails upon discharge. We\nobserve that the silos sustain filling heights significantly above an\nestimation obtained by coupling standard shell-buckling and granular stress\ndistribution theories. Two effects contribute to stabilize the structure: (i)\nbelow the critical filling height, a dynamical stabilization due to granular\nwall friction prevents the localized shell-buckling modes to grow irreversibly;\n(ii) above the critical filling height, collapse occurs before the downward\nsliding motion of the whole granular column sets in, such that only a partial\nfriction mobilization is at play. However, we notice also that the critical\nfilling height is reduced as the grain size, $d$, increases. The importance of\ngrain size contribution is controlled by the ratio $d/\\sqrt{R t}$. We\nrationalize these antagonist effects with a novel fluid/structure theory both\naccounting for the actual status of granular friction at the wall and the\ninherent shell imperfections mediated by the grains. This theory yields new\nscaling predictions which are compared with the experimental results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Jul 2012 00:04:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 6 Jul 2012 22:32:51 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 5 Dec 2014 17:16:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-12-08"}
